==Old English==
===Etymology===
From West Germanic ''*mangian-'', from Indo-European ''*menk-'' ‘knead’.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[menza]], Old Saxon [[mengian]] (Dutch [[mengen]]), Old High German [[mengen]] (German [[mengen]]).  The IE root is also the source of Slavic ''*mekъkъ'' (Old Church Slavonic [[мѫка]], Russian [[мука]]), Baltic ''*minki-'' (Lithuanian [[minkiti]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'meŋgan/

===Verb===
'''mengan''' (class 1 weak)
# to [[mix]], to [[mingle]] or [[blend]]
#:''Ðæt wæter and seo eorþe wæron gemengede oþ ðone þriddan dæg'': the water and earth were mixed until the third day.

